msgid "Examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:70
msgid "Here are examples using both syntax options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:72
msgid "**Using attribute syntax with a typedef:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:82
msgid "**Using keyword syntax with a typedef:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:92
msgid "**Using attribute syntax with a type directly:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:101
msgid "**Using keyword syntax with a type directly:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:110
msgid ""
"\"Well-defined\" overflow is consistent with two's complement wrap-around "
"semantics and won't be removed via eager compiler optimizations (like some "
"undefined behavior might)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:115
msgid "Promotion Rules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:117
msgid ""
"Overflow behavior types (OBTs) follow the traditional C integer promotion "
"and conversion rules while propagating overflow behavior qualifiers through "
"implicit casts. This ensures compatibility with existing C semantics while "
"maintaining overflow behavior information throughout arithmetic expressions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:122
msgid ""
"The resulting type characteristics for overflow behavior types (OBTs) across "
"a variety of scenarios is detailed below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:125
msgid ""
"**OBT and Standard Integer Type**: The result follows standard C conversion "
"rules, with the OBT qualifier applied to the standard result type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:135
msgid ""
"**Two OBTs with Same Behavior**: When both operands have the same overflow "
"behavior, the result follows standard C arithmetic conversions with that "
"behavior applied."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:147
msgid ""
"**Two OBTs with Different Behaviors**: ``trap`` behavior dominates ``wrap`` "
"behavior. The result follows standard C arithmetic conversions with ``trap`` "
"behavior applied."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:160
msgid "Promotion Rules Summary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:164
msgid "Operation Type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:165
msgid "Result Type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:166
msgid "OBT + Standard Integer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:167
msgid "Standard C conversion result with OBT qualifier applied"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:168
msgid "Same Kind OBTs (both ``wrap`` or both ``trap``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:169
msgid "Standard C conversion result with common overflow behavior"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:170
msgid "Different Kind OBTs (``wrap`` + ``trap``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:171
msgid "Standard C conversion result with ``trap`` behavior (dominance)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:173
msgid "**Overflow Behavior Dominance Rules:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:175
msgid "If either operand has ``trap`` behavior → result has ``trap`` behavior"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:176
msgid ""
"If either operand has ``wrap`` behavior (and neither has ``trap`) → result "
"has ``wrap`` behavior"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:177
msgid "Otherwise → no overflow behavior annotation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:179
msgid ""
"This model preserves traditional C semantics while ensuring overflow "
"behavior information is correctly propagated through arithmetic expressions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:183
msgid "Pointer Semantics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:185
msgid ""
"Overflow behavior types can be used with pointers, where the overflow "
"behavior annotation applies to the pointee type. Pointers to overflow "
"behavior types have specific compatibility and conversion rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:189
msgid "**Pointer Type Compatibility:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:191
msgid ""
"Pointers to overflow behavior types are treated as distinct types from their "
"underlying types and from each other when they have different overflow "
"behaviors. This affects assignment, parameter passing, and other pointer "
"operations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:196
msgid "**Discarding Overflow Behavior:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:198
msgid ""
"When assigning from a overflow behavior annotated type to a regular integer "
"type, the compiler issues a warning about discarding overflow behavior. This "
"is controlled by the ``-Wincompatible-pointer-types-discards-overflow-"
"behavior`` diagnostic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:216
msgid "Conversion Semantics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:218
msgid ""
"Overflow behavior types are implicitly convertible to and from built-in "
"integral types with specific semantics for warnings and constant evaluation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:221
msgid "**Incompatible Overflow Behaviors:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:223
msgid ""
"Attempting to assign or convert between types with incompatible overflow "
"behaviors (``trap`` vs ``wrap``) results in a compilation error, as these "
"represent fundamentally different behavioral contracts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:234
msgid ""
"The Diagnostics section further below details the exact diagnostics Clang "
"provides for overflow behavior types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:238
msgid "Truncation Semantics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:240
msgid ""
"Truncation and overflow are related and are both often desirable in some "
"contexts and undesirable in others. To provide control over these behaviors, "
"overflow behavior types may also be used to control truncation "
"instrumentation at the type level."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:245
msgid ""
"Note that implicit integer truncation is not an undefined behavior in C. Due "
"to this, overflow behavior types make no special guarantees about whether "
"implicit integer truncation is defined or not -- the behavior is simply "
"always defined. Use of overflow behavior types in these contexts only "
"control instrumentation related to truncation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:251
msgid ""
"When an overflow behavior type is involved as the source or destination type "
"of truncation, instrumentation checks behave as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:254
msgid ""
"**One or more types is 'trap'**: Truncation checks are inserted and may "
"issue either a trap or sanitizer warning based on compiler settings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:257
msgid ""
"**One or more types is 'wrap'**: No truncation checks are added regardless "
"of compiler flags because truncation with wrapping behavior well-defined. If "
"any of the types is ``trap`` then the truncation rules match the behavior "
"mentioned above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:262
msgid ""
"**Both types are standard integer types**: Behaviors surrounding standard "
"integer types is unchanged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:275
msgid ""
"Note that truncation itself is a form of overflow behavior - when a value is "
"too large to fit in the destination type, the high-order bits are discarded, "
"which is a wrapping behavior that ``wrap`` types are designed to handle "
"predictably."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:281
msgid "Constant Conversion Semantics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:283
msgid ""
"When converting constant values to overflow behavior types, the behavior "
"depends on the overflow behavior annotation and whether the conversion would "
"change the value:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:287
msgid "**With 'wrap' types:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:289
msgid ""
"Constant conversions that would overflow are accepted without warning when "
"assigning to or explicitly casting to ``wrap`` types, as wrapping is the "
"intended behavior:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:299
msgid "**With 'trap' types:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:301
msgid ""
"Constant conversions that would change the value generate a warning when the "
"destination is a ``trap`` type. This matches the behavior of regular non-OBT "
"constant conversions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:306
msgid "Implicit Conversions Due to Assignment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:308
msgid ""
"Like with the basic integral types in C and C++, types on the right-hand "
"side of an assignment may be implicitly converted to match the left-hand "
"side."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:311
msgid ""
"All built-in integral types can be implicitly converted to an overflow "
"behavior version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:319
msgid ""
"Assigning one overflow behavior type to another is legal only when the two "
"types have matching overflow behavior kinds (i.e., ``wrap`` and ``wrap`` or "
"``trap`` and ``trap``). Assigning overflow behavior types with differing "
"behavior kinds will result in an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:333
msgid ""
"However, conversions between compatible overflow behavior types (same kind, "
"different underlying widths or signedness) are allowed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:342
msgid "C++ Overload Resolution"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:344
msgid ""
"For the purposes of C++ overload set formation, promotions or conversions to "
"and from overflow behavior types are of the same rank as normal integer "
"promotions and conversions. These rules have implications during overload "
"candidate selection which may lead to unexpected but correct ambiguity "
"errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:349
msgid ""
"The example below shows potential ambiguity as matching just the underlying "
"type of an OBT parameter is not enough to precisely pick an overload "
"candidate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:361
msgid ""
"Most integral types can be implicitly converted to match OBT parameter types "
"and this can be done unambiguously in certain cases. Especially, when all "
"other candidates are not implicitly convertible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:375
msgid ""
"Overflow behavior types with differing kinds may also create ambiguity in "
"certain contexts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:387
msgid ""
"Overflow behavior types may also be used as template parameters and used "
"within C ``_Generic`` expressions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:391
msgid "C _Generic Expressions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:393
msgid "Overflow behavior types may be used within C ``_Generic`` expressions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:395
msgid ""
"Overflow behavior types do not match against their underlying types within C "
"``_Generic`` expressions. This means that an OBT will not be considered "
"equivalent to its base type for generic selection purposes. OBTs will match "
"against exact types considering bitwidth, signedness and overflow behavior "
"kind."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:413
msgid "C++ Template Specializations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:415
msgid ""
"Like with ``_Generic``, each OBT is treated as a distinct type for template "
"specialization purposes, enabling precise type-based template selection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../OverflowBehaviorTypes.rst:440
msgid ""
"When no exact template specialization exists for an OBT, it falls back to "
"the default template rather than matching the underlying type "
"specialization, maintaining type safety and avoiding unexpected behavior."
msgstr ""

